results.prompt: What's a good yoga routine for beginners?

anthropic.content:
Here's a gentle beginner yoga routine you can do in 20-30 minutes:

## Warm-up (5 minutes)
- **Child's Pose** - 1 minute, focus on breathing
- **Cat-Cow Pose** - 1 minute, gentle spinal movement
- **Neck and shoulder rolls** - 30 seconds each direction

## Standing Poses (10 minutes)
- **Mountain Pose** - 1 minute, establish grounding
- **Forward Fold** - Hold 1 minute (bend knees if needed)
- **Warrior I** - 1 minute each side
- **Tree Pose** - 30 seconds each side (use wall for support)
- **Triangle Pose** - 1 minute each side

## Seated/Floor Poses (10 minutes)
- **Seated Forward Fold** - 2 minutes
- **Seated Twist** - 1 minute each side
- **Bridge Pose** - Hold for 30 seconds, repeat 2-3 times
- **Happy Baby Pose** - 1 minute
- **Legs up the Wall** - 3 minutes

## Cool Down (5 minutes)
- **Savasana (Corpse Pose)** - 5 minutes of complete relaxation

## Beginner Tips:
- Focus on breath over perfect form
- Use props (blocks, straps, pillows) as needed
- Never force or bounce in poses
- Start with 2-3 sessions per week
- Consider taking a beginner class first

Listen to your body and modify poses as needed!

results.prompt: Should I take a gap year?

**Consider a gap year if:**

Gene therapy is a medical technique that involves introducing genetic material into a patient's cells to treat or prevent disease. The basic idea is to correct defective genes or provide new cellular functions by delivering therapeutic genes to target cells.

## How it works:

**Delivery methods:**
- Viral vectors (modified viruses that can't cause disease)
- Direct injection
- Lipofection (using fat particles)
- Electroporation (using electrical pulses)

**Main approaches:**
- **Gene replacement** - Adding a normal copy of a gene to replace a faulty one
- **Gene editing** - Directly correcting mutations (like with CRISPR)
- **Gene silencing** - Turning off genes that cause problems
- **Immune enhancement** - Boosting the body's ability to fight disease

## Current applications:

- Inherited disorders (like severe combined immunodeficiency)
- Some cancers (CAR-T cell therapy)
- Certain eye diseases
- Hemophilia

## Challenges:

- Ensuring genes reach the right cells
- Controlling gene expression levels
- Avoiding immune reactions
- High costs and complexity
- Ethical considerations

Gene therapy holds great promise for treating previously incurable genetic diseases, though it's still a developing field with ongoing research to improve safety and effectiveness.

results.prompt: Write a Dockerfile for a Node.js app

anthropic.content:
Here's a Dockerfile for a Node.js application with best practices:

```dockerfile
# Use the official Node.js runtime as the base image
# Using LTS (Long Term Support) version for stability
FROM node:18-alpine

# Set the working directory inside the container
WORKDIR /usr/src/app

# Create a non-root user for security
RUN addgroup -g 1001 -S nodejs
RUN adduser -S nextjs -u 1001

# Copy package.json and package-lock.json (if available)
# This is done before copying the entire codebase for better caching
COPY package*.json ./

# Install dependencies
RUN npm ci --only=production && npm cache clean --force

# Copy the rest of the application code
COPY . .

# Change ownership of the app directory to the nodejs user
RUN chown -R nextjs:nodejs /usr/src/app
USER nextjs

# Expose the port the app runs on
EXPOSE 3000

# Define environment variable
ENV NODE_ENV=production

# Health check
HEALTHCHECK --interval=30s --timeout=3s --start-period=5s --retries=3 \
  CMD node healthcheck.js

# Command to run the application
CMD ["node", "index.js"]
```

## Alternative Dockerfile with more advanced features:

```dockerfile
# Multi-stage build for smaller production image
FROM node:18-alpine AS builder

# Set working directory
WORKDIR /usr/src/app

# Copy package files
COPY package*.json ./

# Install all dependencies (including devDependencies)
RUN npm ci

# Copy source code
COPY . .

# Build the application (if you have a build step)
RUN npm run build

# Production stage
FROM node:18-alpine AS production

# Install dumb-init for proper signal handling
RUN apk add --no-cache dumb-init

# Create app directory
WORKDIR /usr/src/app

# Create non-root user
RUN addgroup -g 1001 -S nodejs && \
    adduser -S nextjs -u 1001

# Copy package files
COPY package*.json ./

# Install only production dependencies
RUN npm ci --only=production && \
    npm cache clean --force

# Copy built application from builder stage
COPY --from=builder --chown=nextjs:nodejs /usr/src/app/dist ./dist
COPY --from=builder --chown=nextjs:nodejs /usr/src/app/public ./public

# Copy other necessary files
COPY --chown=nextjs:nodejs . .

# Switch to non-root user
USER nextjs

# Expose port
EXPOSE 3000

# Environment variables
ENV NODE_ENV=production
ENV PORT=3000

# Health check
HEALTHCHECK --interval=30s --timeout=3s --start-period=5s --retries=3 \
  CMD wget --no-verbose --tries=1 --spider http://localhost:3000/health || exit 1

# Use dumb-init to handle signals properly
ENTRYPOINT ["dumb-init", "--"]

# Start the application
CMD ["node", "dist/index.js"]
```

## Don't forget to create a `.dockerignore` file:

```dockerignore
node_modules
npm-debug.log
.git
.gitignore
README.md
.env
.nyc_output

results.prompt: What's the best time to workout?

anthropic.content:
The best time to work out depends on your personal schedule, preferences, and goals, but here are some key considerations:

**Morning (6-9 AM):**
- Often easier to maintain consistency
- May boost energy and mood for the day
- Fewer schedule conflicts
- Some research suggests better fat burning in a fasted state

**Afternoon/Early Evening (3-6 PM):**
- Body temperature is naturally higher, potentially improving performance
- Many people feel strongest during this time
- Good for stress relief after work

**Things to consider:**
- **Consistency matters most** - the "best" time is when you can stick to it regularly
- **Your chronotype** - whether you're naturally a morning person or night owl
- **Your schedule** - work, family, and other commitments
- **Sleep impact** - avoid intense workouts 2-3 hours before bedtime
- **Energy levels** - when do you naturally feel most energetic?

**Bottom line:** The most effective workout time is whenever you can be consistent and give good effort. Try different times for a week each and see what feels best for your body and lifestyle.

What matters more than timing is that you're exercising regularly!

results.prompt: How do I make a website accessible?

anthropic.content:
Here are key practices to make your website accessible:

## Content & Structure
- **Use semantic HTML** (headings h1-h6, nav, main, footer, etc.)
- **Write clear, descriptive headings** that outline your content hierarchy
- **Provide alt text** for images that conveys their purpose or content
- **Use descriptive link text** instead of "click here" or "read more"

## Visual Design
- **Ensure sufficient color contrast** (4.5:1 ratio for normal text, 3:1 for large text)
- **Don't rely solely on color** to convey information
- **Make text resizable** up to 200% without horizontal scrolling
- **Design for different screen sizes** and orientations

## Navigation & Interaction
- **Make all functionality keyboard accessible** (Tab, Enter, Arrow keys)
- **Provide visible focus indicators** for keyboard users
- **Give users enough time** to read content (avoid auto-advancing carousels)
- **Avoid content that flashes** more than 3 times per second

## Technical Implementation
- **Use proper form labels** and error messages
- **Add ARIA labels** when HTML semantics aren't enough
- **Test with screen readers** like NVDA, JAWS, or VoiceOver
- **Validate your HTML** to ensure clean, semantic markup

## Testing
- Navigate your site using only a keyboard
- Use accessibility checking tools like axe or WAVE
- Test with actual assistive technologies
- Consider hiring users with disabilities for testing

Start with these fundamentals and gradually implement more advanced accessibility features as you learn.
